le. Democracy demands that ordinary citizens negotiate the tension between these often conflicting impulses. Aristophanes' comedies rest upon and seek to instill in spectators a complex comic disposition that holds a simple celebration of rebellion in tension with an appreciation for the organized collective action necessary to bring about real change. John Zumbrunnen is professor of political science at the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and the author of Silence and Democracy: Athenian Politics in Thucydides' History as well as numerous articles and essays.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenship in literature. 0aCitizenship. 0aDemocracy in literature. 0aDemocracy. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAncient Democracy.  aAncient Greece.  aAristophanes.  aAthenian society.  aAthens.  aAuthor.  aCitizenship.  aComic playwright.  aDemocracy.  aDemocratic theory.  aDrama.  aGreek Politics.  aOld Comedy.  aPlay.  aPlaywright.  aPoet.  aPolitical theory.  aPopulism.  aRhetoric.  aSatire.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046771140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580467711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580467711/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles